  <h1>TDS on payments to non-residents under Section 195</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>7 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>Section 195 requires any person paying a non-resident a sum chargeable to tax in India to deduct TDS at the rates in force, applying the more beneficial of the Income-tax Act or the relevant DTAA.</b> A CA certificate in Form 15CB and a declaration in Form 15CA are generally required before remittance.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">Scope of Section 195</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Act rate vs DTAA rate</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Forms 15CA and 15CB</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Grossing up and lower deduction</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">Scope of Section 195</h2>
<p>Section 195 applies to <b>any sum chargeable to tax</b> in India paid to a non-resident &mdash; interest, royalty, fees for technical services, capital gains, and other income. It does not apply to salary (covered by Section 192) or to sums not chargeable to tax in India. The payer must determine taxability and the correct rate before paying.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Act rate vs DTAA rate</h2>
<p>The deductor applies the <b>more beneficial</b> of the rate under the Act or the applicable DTAA. To claim the treaty rate, the non-resident must furnish a <b>Tax Residency Certificate (TRC)</b>, Form 10F, and (where required) a no-PE declaration. Without these, the higher Act rate (and the Section 206AA fallback where no PAN) may apply.</p><div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Payment</th><th>Typical treaty rate (illustrative)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Royalty / FTS</td><td>10% (varies by treaty)</td></tr><tr><td>Interest</td><td>10%-15% (varies)</td></tr><tr><td>Dividend</td><td>5%-15% (varies)</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p><span style="font-size:11px;color:var(--emerald,#34d399);font-weight:600">✓ Verified June 2026</span> the exact rate in the specific DTAA article for the payment.</p>

  <h2 id="s2">Forms 15CA and 15CB</h2>
<ul><li><b>Form 15CB</b> &mdash; a CA's certificate on the taxability and rate, required for most taxable foreign remittances above the threshold.</li><li><b>Form 15CA</b> &mdash; the remitter's declaration, filed online, referencing 15CB.</li><li>Certain payments in the specified list (Rule 37BB) are exempt from 15CA/15CB.</li></ul>

  <h2 id="s3">Grossing up and lower deduction</h2>
<p>If the contract is <b>net of tax</b>, the income is <b>grossed up</b> under Section 195A so the TDS is borne by the payer. To avoid over-deduction, the payer can apply under <b>Section 195(2)</b> for a determination of the taxable portion, or the payee can seek a <a href="lower-tds-certificate-section-197.html">lower-deduction certificate under Section 197</a>.</p>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>When does Section 195 TDS apply?</summary><p>On any sum chargeable to tax in India that is paid to a non-resident &mdash; such as royalty, fees for technical services, interest or capital gains &mdash; other than salary.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Can I apply the DTAA rate?</summary><p>Yes, the more beneficial of the Act or DTAA rate applies, provided the non-resident furnishes a Tax Residency Certificate, Form 10F and, where relevant, a no-PE declaration.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Are Forms 15CA and 15CB always required?</summary><p>Most taxable foreign remittances require them, but a specified list of payments under Rule 37BB is exempt from the 15CA/15CB requirement.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>195 covers any India-taxable sum paid to a non-resident.</li><li>Apply the more beneficial of the Act or DTAA rate (TRC + 10F).</li><li>Form 15CB (CA certificate) + 15CA (declaration) before remittance.</li><li>Net-of-tax contracts are grossed up under Section 195A.</li></ul>
  </div>

